  "prompt": "Why are diesel engines more efficient than gasoline engines?",
  "response": "Diesel engines are generally more efficient than gasoline engines for several key reasons:\n\n1. Compression Ratio\n- Diesel engines have higher compression ratios (typically 14:1 to 25:1)\n- Higher compression allows more energy extraction from fuel\n- Leads to greater thermal efficiency\n\n2. Fuel Characteristics\n- Diesel fuel has higher energy density than gasoline\n- Contains more potential energy per volume\n- Less refined, which reduces production costs\n\n3. Combustion Process\n- Diesel engines use compression-ignition instead of spark plugs\n- Direct injection allows more precise fuel control\n- Leaner air-fuel mixture means more complete combustion\n\n4. Engine Design\n- Diesel engines are typically built more robustly\n- Can withstand higher pressures and temperatures\n- Allows for more mechanical efficiency\n\n5. Lower Throttling Losses\n- Diesel engines regulate power by fuel quantity, not air restriction\n- Reduces energy wasted in restricting air intake\n- More consistent energy conversion\n\nThese factors combine to make diesel engines approximately 20-35% more fuel-efficient than comparable gasoline engines, though they often have higher initial manufacturing costs.",
